<section class="block-paragraph">
<h3 data-block-key="l0ztk">Step 2: Choose your first ETFs.</h3><p data-block-key="9ojmo">For beginners, passive index funds are generally the best way to go. Index funds are cheaper than their actively managed counterparts, and the reality is that most actively managed funds <i>dont</i> beat their benchmark index over time.</p><p data-block-key="bkp0o">With that in mind, heres a list of ETFs, and a brief description of what each invests in, for beginners who are just starting to build their portfolios:</p>
</section>
<section class="block-paragraph">
<h2 class="toc-target" data-block-key="b17i1">10 of the Best ETFs for Beginners</h2><h2 data-block-key="a51j0">ETF Examples: 10 of the Best ETFs for Beginners</h2><ol><li data-block-key="7t0mz"><b>Vanguard S&amp;P 500 ETF</b> (<span class="font-bold whitespace-nowrap" data-id="248475"><a href="/quote/nysemkt/voo/">VOO</a> <span class="text-red-900 ticker-change"> -0.73%</span></span>) -- Large U.S. companies</li><li data-block-key="n1zo3"><b>Schwab U.S. Mid-Cap ETF</b> (<span class="font-bold whitespace-nowrap" data-id="225337"><a href="/quote/nysemkt/schm/">SCHM</a> <span class="text-red-900 ticker-change"> -1.33%</span></span>) -- Midsize U.S. companies</li><li data-block-key="4fctk"><b>Vanguard Russell 2000 ETF</b> (<a href="/quote/nysemkt/vtwo/">NYSEMKT:VTWO</a>) -- Smaller U.S. companies</li><li data-block-key="ufe4d"><b>Schwab International Equity ETF</b> (<span class="font-bold whitespace-nowrap" data-id="225002"><a href="/quote/nysemkt/schf/">SCHF</a> <span class="text-red-900 ticker-change"> -0.09%</span></span>) -- Larger non-U.S. companies</li><li data-block-key="wigg1"><b>Schwab Emerging Markets Equity ETF</b> (<span class="font-bold whitespace-nowrap" data-id="225338"><a href="/quote/nysemkt/sche/">SCHE</a> <span class="text-green-900 ticker-change"> 0.79%</span></span>) -- Companies from countries with developing economies</li><li data-block-key="hn44f"><b>Vanguard High-Dividend ETF</b> (<span class="font-bold whitespace-nowrap" data-id="221825"><a href="/quote/nysemkt/vym/">VYM</a> <span class="text-red-900 ticker-change"> -1.0%</span></span>) -- Stocks that pay above-average dividends</li><li data-block-key="wl7k0"><b>Schwab U.S. REIT ETF</b> (<span class="font-bold whitespace-nowrap" data-id="225339"><a href="/quote/nysemkt/schh/">SCHH</a> <span class="text-green-900 ticker-change"> 0.95%</span></span>) -- Real estate investment trusts</li><li data-block-key="u21ef"><b>Schwab U.S. Aggregate Bond ETF</b> (<span class="font-bold whitespace-nowrap" data-id="250170"><a href="/quote/nysemkt/schz/">SCHZ</a> <span class="text-red-900 ticker-change"> -0.09%</span></span>) -- Bonds of all different varieties and maturity lengths</li><li data-block-key="8m894"><b>Vanguard Total World Bond Fund</b> (<span class="font-bold whitespace-nowrap" data-id="342452"><a href="/quote/nasdaq/bndw/">BNDW</a> <span class="text-green-900 ticker-change"> 0.03%</span></span>) -- Includes international bonds as well as U.S. bonds of various lengths and maturities.</li><li data-block-key="579a5"><b>Invesco QQQ Trust</b> (<span class="font-bold whitespace-nowrap" data-id="206254"><a href="/quote/nasdaq/qqq/">QQQ</a> <span class="text-red-900 ticker-change"> -0.35%</span></span>) - Tracks the Nasdaq-100 Index, which is heavy on tech and other growth stocks.</li></ol><p data-block-key="wfdak">You might notice that this list is heavy on Vanguard and Schwab. Theres a good reason for this: Both are dedicated to offering Americans access to the stock market at a minimal expense, so ETFs from both tend to be among the cheapest in the business.</p>
</section>
