<section class="block-paragraph">
<h3 data-block-key="0vm2e">Step 3: Let your ETFs do the hard work for you.</h3><p data-block-key="emq4f">Its important to keep in mind that ETFs are generally designed to be maintenance-free investments.</p><p data-block-key="2pjq6">Newer investors tend to have a bad habit of checking their portfolios far too often, and making emotional, knee-jerk reactions to major market moves. In fact, the average fund investor significantly underperforms the market over time, and over-trading is the main reason. So, once you buy shares of some great ETFs, the best advice is to <i>leave them alone</i> and let them do what theyre intended to do: produce excellent investment growth over long periods of time.</p>
</section>
